```rust
fn security_prompt(rel_path: &str, accept_all: &mut bool) -> Result<bool, String> {
    if *accept_all {
        return Ok(true);
    }

    use std::io::Write;
    eprint!("Security: sync '{}' to root-owned target? [y]es [n]o [a]ll [q]uit: ", rel_path);
    std::io::stderr().flush().map_err(|e| format!("flush: {}", e))?;

    let mut input = String::new();
    std::io::stdin().read_line(&mut input).map_err(|e| format!("read: {}", e))?;

    match input.trim().to_lowercase().as_str() {
        "a" => {
            *accept_all = true;
            Ok(true)
        }
        "y" => Ok(true),
        "q" => Err("Aborted by user due to security confirmation.".to_string()),
        _ => Ok(false),
    }
}
```

Now for integration in the sync loops. In the non-interactive loop (first loop), I'll add a security check inside the CopyToTarget and DeleteTarget match arms. In the interactive loop (second loop), I'll add the same check.

Let me think about how to integrate this cleanly without too much code duplication. One option is to create a helper function that wraps the security check:

```rust
fn handle_security_check(
    rel_path: &str,
    group_index: usize,
    security_needed: &[bool],
    security_accept_all: &mut bool,
    outcome: &mut SyncOutcome,
) -> Result<bool, String> {
    if !security_needed[group_index] {
        return Ok(true);
    }

    match security_prompt(rel_path, security_accept_all) {
        Ok(true) => Ok(true),
        Ok(false) => {
            eprintln!("  skipped (security): {}", rel_path);
            outcome.skipped_perms += 1;
            Ok(false)
        },
        Err(e) => Err(e),
    }
}
```

Then in the match arms:
```rust
Change::CopyToTarget { rel_path, abs_src, abs_tgt, group_index, .. } if !interactive => {
    if !handle_security_check(rel_path, *group_index, &security_needed, &mut security_accept_all, &mut outcome)? {
        continue;
    }
    // existing code...
}
```

